# 🚀 CI/CD Pipeline using Jenkins & Docker

A hands-on project demonstrating how to build a complete CI/CD pipeline using Jenkins for automation and Docker for containerization.

---

## 📌 Project Overview

This project automates the process of building, testing, and deploying an application using Jenkins pipelines and Docker containers. Any code pushed to GitHub automatically triggers a build and deployment.

---

## 🛠️ Tools & Services Used

- Jenkins (CI/CD Automation)
- Docker (Containerization)
- GitHub (Source Code Management)
- Linux (Ubuntu Server)

---

## 📋 What I Did — Step by Step

### 1. Set Up Jenkins on Linux Server
- Installed Java (required for Jenkins) on Ubuntu
- Installed and configured Jenkins
- Accessed Jenkins dashboard via browser on port `8080`

### 2. Installed Required Jenkins Plugins
- Git Plugin — to pull code from GitHub
- Docker Pipeline Plugin — to build and run Docker containers
- GitHub Integration Plugin — for automatic build triggers

### 3. Connected GitHub to Jenkins
- Created a GitHub repository for the project
- Configured Jenkins to connect to GitHub using credentials
- Set up a **Webhook** in GitHub so that every code push automatically triggers a Jenkins build

### 4. Created a Dockerfile
- Wrote a Dockerfile to containerize the application
- The Dockerfile defines the base image, copies the app code, and sets up the run command

```dockerfile
# Sample Dockerfile
FROM ubuntu:20.04
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y nginx
COPY . /var/www/html
EXPOSE 80
CMD ["nginx", "-g", "daemon off;"]
```

### 5. Created a Jenkins Pipeline (Jenkinsfile)
- Wrote a Jenkinsfile to define the CI/CD stages

```groovy
pipeline {
    agent any
    stages {
        stage('Clone Repository') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/prasanth17-cloud/cicd-jenkins-docker'
            }
        }
        stage('Build Docker Image') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker build -t myapp:latest .'
            }
        }
        stage('Run Docker Container') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker stop myapp || true'
                sh 'docker rm myapp || true'
                sh 'docker run -d --name myapp -p 80:80 myapp:latest'
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### 6. Tested the Full Pipeline
- Pushed code changes to GitHub
- Jenkins automatically detected the push via Webhook
- Pipeline ran all 3 stages: Clone → Build → Deploy
- Application was live inside a Docker container

